<HEADLINE>
Pope Benedict XVI arrives to address Australian vigil
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Pope Benedict XVI arrived at a Sydney racecourse to address a
candlelit vigil attended by tens of thousands for the Catholic
church's World Youth Day on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The pope arrived at 7:15 pm (0915 GMT) to a rapturous welcome,
waving to the crowd to religious music.
</P>
<P>
Organisers said more than 200,000 young Catholics would gather at
the Royal Randwick Racecourse in eastern Sydney where the pontiff
was to address a prayer session, as the world's largest Christian
festival approaches its conclusion.
</P>
<P>
A giant cross overshadowed the stage where Pope Benedict was to
address the crowd, where dancers dressed in white performed ahead
of his arrival, to the sound of religious songs.
</P>
<P>
Australia's biggest city has been transformed by the estimated
215,000 worshippers from around the country and the world who are
in Sydney for a six- day Catholic youth celebration led by the 81
-year-old pontiff.
</P>
